description:
Moneyball combines euro-style mechanics and the latest in advanced analytics (Sabermetrics) to build a true 21st century tabletop baseball simulation. Moneyball plays faster, smoother, and more accurately than anything before it. Player cards are not jammed with complicated and unsightly dice tables, just 5 straightforward 1-10 ratings for hitters (Contact, Patience, Power, Bunting, Baserunning) and pitchers (Control, Velocity, Repertoire, Move, and Stamina). There are no dice rolls with multiples charts to reference, just a simple card draw for the pitcher and chit draw for the batter.

Run your front office like a real front office by evaluating talent using the same metrics actual scouts and GMs use today. Not the stats of yesteryear. With advanced Sabermetrics, we've learned there are just a handful of underlying statistics that determine a player's performance. For pitchers the only stats that really matter are his walk, strikeout and fly ball rate. It&rsquo;s been statistically proven that a pitcher&rsquo;s &ldquo;stuff&rdquo; has very little influence on the outcome once a ball is a play. It&rsquo;s much more dependent on the stadium, weather, the defense behind him, and pure luck &ndash; all factors beyond his control. For hitters, strike out and line drive rates, more than anything, determine their batting average. Moneyball has been built from the ground up using these underlying principles.

Pitchers are streakier than hitters and are therefore modeled differently in Moneyball. Their performance is highly volatile and can vary greatly from game to game because your starting pitcher&rsquo;s draw deck is constructed before each game. The pitcher deck, which determines strike outs, walks, and home runs consists of 108 cards. Your starter&rsquo;s deck has only 36 of those cards and it is typically reshuffled several times each start. One of your roles as the manager is to evaluate his &ldquo;stuff&rdquo; as the game progresses. This creates fantastic &ldquo;heat of the moment&rdquo; decision making that does not exist in other baseball sims. If your starter is wilder than usual or has served up several gopher balls, it&rsquo;s probably because he didn&rsquo;t have his best &ldquo;stuff&rdquo; i.e. his draw deck has more walk and home run cards than usual. So recognizing when your starter doesn&rsquo;t have his best stuff and yanking him is CRUCIAL to your success as a manager. Starters in Moneyball are not purely random dice rolls with a backwards cause-and-effect &ldquo;fatigue&rdquo; modifier added after they&rsquo;ve already gotten lit up. Manage your starting pitcher like a real manager, not a dice roller&hellip;

Contrabando: Vale do C&ocirc;a is an adventure game based on ethnographic research about smuggling on the eastern border of Northern Portugal, during Salazar&rsquo;s dictatorship.

Each player controls both smugglers and border officers, on one hand trying to guide his own smugglers to Spain and on another trying to catch the other players smugglers. On each of the six nights of the game, each player guides two groups, but every group has a different number of members and cargo value, as well as different points of departure and arrival. So movement must be planned and sometimes a group must be sacrifice in order to save other. The length of each group's journey, the value of its cargo and the phase of the moon influences the strategy as for example, on a full moon, the officers can better see and thus control the territory. Also there are different terrains like forests, unpredictable and dangerous lookout points, mounts and a canyon river (the Douro, famous for the Port wine) influence the movement and hiding capacities of the smugglers. The action cards add different dynamics to the game allowing to momentarily break the rules and get a flavor of the tactics of both smugglers and officers.

"Night is falling. Amidst the silence and shadows of the villages, men and women leave their homes with suspicious bags. Walking for hours and hours, they cross mounts and valleys, smuggling merchandise to Spain. But the portuguese border force officers know the paths and are always on the lookout for the nightly adventurers. This game, based on the heritage of Territ&oacute;rios do C&ocirc;a relives the smuggling stories from the period of the portuguese dictatorship. Can you get to Spain?&rdquo;

Privateers! The Golden Decade is a competitive boardgame for 2 to 5 players that takes the life of 18th Century's piracy on your table. Players will impersonate a pirate sailing the high seas among isles to conquer them all. Pirates will hunt treasures, loot merchants and sell goods to the colonies, avoiding dangerous storms, reefs and shoal-filled waters. They will trade ships for better and bigger ones or improve them with sails, crew and weapons in order to fight each other.

Every pirate starts the game with:  

     a standard ship card of 100 doubloons value with: movement of six, basic weapons, one crew man to repair the damaged tokens and empty slots where to put markers of canvas or every other markers in the hold; 
     twenty doubloons; 
     a command token, that let the pirates do special action during the play; 
     a load pawn and a ship pawn (to represent the ship on the board); 
     four pirate coves tokens, to put on the national flags when a pirate has conquered that national city.



Sailing around the modules, every player can freely attack the colonial ships, that are moved by the wind, or the other players, to steal doubloons or equipment tokens. The attack start when two ships are on the same tile. Every contender takes his three combat cards, that match the weapon token on his ship (or the basic weapon) and chose secretly one of them. When both the contenders had chosen their card, they flip them at the same time and they compare the two cards to see the result.

At the end of his own turn, each player has to generate one of the six events spinning the Wind Rose and immediately has to perform the related action: Diplomacy, Kraken, Castaway, Buried Treasure, Storm, Colonial Ship.

Once the game ends the scores are assigned to the players according to the following conditions: 
Retained doubloons;
Owned ship;
Retained command tokens;
Owned cities
Equipment tokens, even if damaged
The player who has got the highest score is the winner.

Starting from the idea "A territory an action" to Isle at War I rebuilt the game by adding my ideas and other games trying to keep it simple and fun intact.

The variations are:

I added an action called "Alliances" in which you draw a card from the Allies that can make a additional action; 
I replaced the original map with a modular hexagons; 
You can play up to 4 players; 
The territory with the castle can produce 2 troops; 
The game lasts 10 rounds; 
The player with the most points in this way: 
1 point for a territory; 
3 points for the special territory; 
1 to 3 points for cards Allies; 
At the end of any turn, the player with more than half the territories may declare the end of the game.

Enjoy!

Alessandro

The game of jet fighters air combat in the imaginary battle.

There are 28 different jets (US, USSR, GB, FR, JAP, etc...) each detailed on a separate card with its vital statistics.
It seems quite close to Air War.

This game use simultaneous movement like those used in the SPI games.

Components :

- 8 maps;
- 1 rules manual;
- 2 sheets about missiles;
- 2 sheets of charts and tables;
- 580 counters;
- 1 Simultaneous Movement pad;
- 2 six sided dice

The Beta Team Expansion box will include the stretch goals NOT exclusive of the Kickstarter campaign.

The full contents of the Beta Team box are:

- 5 Heroes, featuring Freder, Elle, Kanga, Polly, and Will; 
- 12 Upgrade Cards, featuring 6 new cards; 
- 3 Hero Dice;
- 5 Old Town Tiles, including a Maps Leaflet;
- 6 Corrupted Police Acolyte Miniatures, featuring 3 different sculpts and their Acolyte Board;
- 6 Corrupted Fireman Acolyte Miniatures, featuring 3 different sculpts and their Acolyte Board.
